\begin_layout Section
Evolutionary Trajectory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A genome is denoted by a list of signed numbers, each of which represents
 a gene with sign being a direction of transcription.
 Numbers can be repetitive to denote members of a family.
 Two genomes, for example, can be given as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset Formula $i:$
\end_inset

1 2 2 -4 5 3 2 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset Formula $j:$
\end_inset

 2 2 -4 -4 -4 -3 5 6
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I want to study rates of gain, loss, duplication, and inversion using two
 genomes codied by signed numbers.
 The instantaneous rate of change from genome 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{i,j}=\begin{cases}
\kappa & \mathrm{gain}\\
\mu & \mathrm{loss}\\
\lambda & \mathrm{duplication}\\
\alpha & \mathrm{Inversion}\end{cases}.\]

\end_inset

 The posterior probability of genome evolutionary path (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

) and the set of four rate parameters (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

) is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\Pr(\rho,\theta|i,j) & =\frac{\Pr(i,j|\rho,\theta)\Pr(\rho,\theta)}{\Pr(i,j)}\\
 & =\frac{\Pr(j,\rho|i,\theta)\Pr(i|\theta)\Pr(\rho)\Pr(\theta)}{\Pr(i,j)}.\end{align*}

\end_inset

A path of the genome evolution denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a record of four events and their event time.
 Total number of events along the path is 
\begin_inset Formula $Z.$
\end_inset

 A path starts at genome 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and ends in 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $i(0)=i,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i(Z+1)=j.$
\end_inset

 I call 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr(j,\rho|i,\theta)$
\end_inset

 path probability, which is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\Pr(j,\rho|i,\theta)= & \prod_{z=1}^{Z}\frac{R_{i(z-1),i(z)}}{R_{i(z-1),\bullet}}R_{i(z-1),\bullet}e^{-R_{i(z-1),\bullet}(t(z)-t(z-1))}\times e^{-R_{i(Z-1),\bullet}(t(Z+1)-t(Z))}\\
= & \kappa^{n_{\mathrm{gain}}}\mu^{n_{\mathrm{loss}}}\lambda^{n_{\mathrm{duplication}}}\alpha^{n_{\mathrm{inversion}}}\prod_{z=1}^{Z+1}e^{-R_{i(z-1),\bullet}(t(z)-t(z-1))}\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the rate away from a genome 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{i,\bullet}=(n_{i}+1)\kappa+n_{i}\mu+n_{i}\lambda+n_{i}(n_{i}-1)\alpha/2.\]

\end_inset

The probability of a genome given the set of four rate parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr(i|\theta),$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\Pr(i|\theta)= & \Pr(i,n_{i}|\theta)\\
= & \Pr(i|n_{i},\theta)\Pr(n_{i}|\theta)\\
= & \left(1/T\right)^{n_{i}}\Pr(n_{i}|\theta)\\
= & \left(1/T\right)^{n_{i}}\left(1-\frac{\kappa+\lambda}{\mu}\right)\left(\frac{\kappa+\lambda}{\mu}\right)^{n_{i}}\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the number genes of genome 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the maximum number of available genes.
 I assume that the maximum number of genes is the total number of genes
 we observe in the data.
 That being said, I must construct an initial path of the genome evolution;
 an inversion history of signed permutation is first made, and gene gain,
 loss, and duplication events can be added to the history.
 I may use 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Miklos2009"

\end_inset

 to sample inversion history, which I then embellish with gene gain, loss,
 and duplication events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method above can be useful to infer detailed history of genome evolution.
 It could be extended to embody more realistic evolutionary models, and
 could provide basis of statistical genome alignment.
\end_layout

