\begin_layout Section
Preferential gain and geometric loss
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A CRISPR locus gains a spacer at the adjacent to the leader element: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{L}\rightarrow a^{*}a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{L}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{l}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

-th spacer and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the newly prepended spacer.
 The CRISPR locus loses one of the spacers:
\begin_inset Formula \[
a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{d-1}a_{d}a_{d+1}\cdots a_{L}\rightarrow a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{d-1}a_{d+1}\cdots a_{L}\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-th spacer is deleted.
 The rate of loss of a spacer is qualitatively proportional to the distance
 of the spacer to the leader element.
 The rate of preferential spacer gain and geometric loss position from spacer
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
R_{i,j}=\begin{cases}
\mu_{d} & d\mathrm{-th}\:\mathrm{one\: spacer\: loss}\\
\lambda & \mathrm{one\: spacer\: gain}\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{d}=M\times(1-\alpha(1-\alpha)^{d-1}),$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\alpha<1,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\mathbb{N}=\{1,2,3,\ldots\}.$
\end_inset

 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\emptyset & \rightarrow & 1\\
1 & \rightarrow & \begin{cases}
2,1 & \mathrm{gain}\\
\emptyset & \mathrm{loss}\end{cases}\\
2,1 & \rightarrow & \begin{cases}
3,2,1 & \mathrm{gain}\\
1 & \mathrm{loss}\\
2 & \mathrm{loss}\end{cases}\\
3,2,1 & \rightarrow & \begin{cases}
4,3,2,1 & \mathrm{gain}\\
3,2 & \mathrm{loss}\\
3,1 & \mathrm{loss}\\
2,1 & \mathrm{loss}\end{cases}\\
 & \cdots\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where numbers represent spacers and 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 is no spacers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After episodic thoughts of a few days, I think that an insertion-deletion
 model of sequences could be applied to model the spacer gain and loss evolution
 of CRISPR.
 Differences between this gain-loss evolution of CRISPR and the indel (with
 substitution) include: 1.
 No substitutions are allowed in CRISPR, 2.
 Insertion and deletion are preferentially occurring, or insertion at the
 front of the repetitive element, and deletion rate is proportional to the
 distance from leader, and 3.
 number of character states vary depending on data under study.
 The alignment uncertainty of CRISPR repetitive elements is not high, and
 I would assume that trees are given by other source of information.
 I am interested in gain and loss rates along lineages of a tree.
\end_layout

